title: [PINOT-3200] Adding capability in broker to select HLC or LLC segments for routing based on a selector class
body:
In order to migrate live use cases to use low-level kafka consumers, we need to have them generate both high-level
as well as low-level kafka segments for sometime, and have the brokers route some percentage of requests to low-level
segments. We increase the percentage over time, until we route only to low-level segments, and then drop
the high-level kafka segments later.

This PR addresses the capability in the broker to be able to selectively route requests according to a
specified selector class (configurable).

The feature of being able to specify a RoutingTable class has been removed to reduce the complexity of handling
low-level segment routing while still having a custom class for high-level and other segments.

Updating the broker tenant config can drop additional broker instances
when down scaling. A serious side-effect of this is that when Helix is
requested to drop this instance, it does not remove its reference from
the BrokerResource in IdealState. This breaks all future calls to query
instances with a specific tag from Helix. While this PR only addresses
the bug in Pinot, the Helix issue would/should be investigated
separately.

title: TE: Create multi-dimensional summary for week-over-week change of metric
body:
This is a prototype for creating a summary for week-over-week changes in a dataset. 

=== To create a summary ===
Start ThirdEyeDashboardApplication and curl this URL: http://localhost:1426/dashboard/summary/autoDimensionOrder.
The available parameters are:
  **dataset** and **metrics**: a sring,
  **baselineStart** and **currentStart**: in ISO format,
  **aggTimeGranularity**: DAYS or HOURS,
  **dimensions**: multiple strings separated by ","
  **hierarchies**: a JSon string of List<List<String>>; each sub-list<String> define a hierarchical dimension (e.g., ["continent","countryCode"]) and the string appears first has the highest level in the hierarchy,
  **topDimensions**: number of dimensions to drill down (suggested value: <4),
  **oneSideError**: true or false; once it is turned on, only detailed rows that has the same trend of change as the top aggregated row are shown,
  **summarySize**: the length of the summary.

**Example**: http://localhost:1426/dashboard/summary/autoDimensionOrder?dataset=thirdeyeKbmi&metrics=pageViews&baselineStart=1467788400000&currentStart=1468393200000&aggTimeGranularity=DAYS&dimensions=browserName,continent,countryCode,deviceName,environment,locale,osName,pageKey,service,sourceApp&hierarchies=[["continent","countryCode"]]&topDimensions=3&oneSideError=true&summarySize=10

title: Simulate function triggers across time range
body:
Adding a new endpoint to run an anomaly function spec for all the fire times that would have appeared during a given [start,end) time range, based on the cron schedule in the function spec. The otherwise equivalent functionality would require manually calculating the fire times and submitting a curl call to the adhoc endpoint.

Another key difference is that the adhoc calls allow for explicitly defining the data input range. This simulation endpoint only defines the start/end of scheduled fire times, so the data input is determined based on the anomaly function spec's data window.

title: Disabling retention in integration tests.
body:
```
During a recent debugging of integration test failure, it was found that
we set a retention value of 900 days during setting up tables for
integration tests. Most these tests use the airline data for which some
records are now > 900 days old, and getting deleted during the test.

The fix is to disable retention by not setting valid retention time
value and unit.
```

title: Make the padding character configurable and change it to the null character.
body:
By default the padding character will continue to be '\0' but it can be
changed to any other character. This will automatically support segments generated with the the current default
'%' and with no padding character specified in the metadata.
This change fixes the case when the column value has a trailing percent, which results in wrong results.
